TextChange:
When does life begin? This is a question for the ages. Some people believe that life begins at conception, others at birth. This is one of the issues at the heart of the abortion debate.

I believe that a person begins life once you detect a human heartbeat however, that is my own personal opinion. That being said, I do belive that it is a woman's choice to decide if she will carry a baby to term. It's not a simple choice as some people would have you beleive. It's not a choice like choosing a Mounds candy bar over an Almond Joy. It's a choice that will be with you the rest of your life. 

There are many reasons women choose not to carry a baby to term. Sometimes it is because the woman's health is at stake. Their are instances when a woman became pregnant as a result of trauma, such as rape or incest. Sometimes it's a financial decision. This is hard to imagine, but if you're living paycheck to paycheck, it's difficult to decide how you will cope with another mouth to feed. And then it's also possible that you get pregnant at an impossible time in your life. For instance, if you've just been accepted to college or some other opportunity that you've dreamed of all your life, and now you won't be able to do it because you have a baby.

Some people say you should carry the baby to term and then put it up for adoption. Okay, but that's nine months out of your life that you give up to be a human incubator for someone else. Also, if that baby is born with special needs, what are its chances for adoption. There are also health risks with being pregnant that can lead to death or lifelong disability. 

Some people believe that life begins at conception. If this is true, a person the size of a tadpole would be protected by 1st Amendment rights,  would be entitled to a lawyer and any number of other rights that we take for granted.

In conclusion, whether you are dead or alive, nobody can remove any of your organs without your permission and if you haven't made arrangements for that, your spouse or family makes that decision. If someone has no right to my kidney or liver, how can they tell me whether or not I have to carry a baby to term?
